Question

A canoe travels 2.9 m/s relative to the water. A river, heading east, flows at 1.4 m/s. The canoe points at a direction 2.24 radians counterclockwise from east.


Find the canoes total speed, in m/s, and direction of travel, as radians counterclockwise from east. (In other words, find the canoes velocity relative to the ground, in polar form.)

  • Speed = ##ANSWER1##
  • Direction = ##ANSWER2##

Answerlist

  • 1.9
  • 2.0
  • 2.1
  • 2.2
  • 2.3
  • 2.4
  • 1.71
  • 1.72
  • 1.73
  • 1.74
  • 1.75
  • 1.76

Solution

First, find the rectangular coordinates of each velocity vector. The two formulas:

\[x~=~r\cdot\cos(\theta)\] \[y~=~r\cdot\sin(\theta)\]

We will use \(\vec{v}_1\) for the canoes velocity relative to water. It is shown below with approximate rectangular coordinates (found from formulas above, using \(r=2.9\) and \(\theta=2.24\)).

\[\vec{v}_1 = (-1.799,2.275)\]

We will use \(\vec{v}_2\) for the rivers velocity vector. Since the river flows directly east, all of its speed is in the positive horizontal direction.

\[\vec{v}_2 = (1.400,0.000)\]

Now, add the corresponding components to find \(\vec{v}_3\), the velocity of the canoe relative to the ground.

\[\vec{v}_3 = (-0.399,2.275)\]

Lastly, we need to find the polar coordinates. The formulas are given below. Notice, I am using the two-argument arctangent function.

\[r~=~\sqrt{x^2+y^2}\] \[\theta~=~\arctan(y,x)\]

So,

\[r=\sqrt{(-0.399)^2+(2.275)^2}~=~2.3092561\]

\[\theta=\arctan(2.275,-0.399)~=~1.7444721\]

This can be visualized.



So, if we round like the answer choices, the speed of the canoe is 2.3 m/s at a direction of 1.74 radians counterclockwise from east.
